      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
      "body" : "@MarinosAn What do you mean exactly? MI with traits that contain concrete methods, e.g. <code>class C extends A with B</code>, is implemented with normal interfaces <code>A</code> and <code>B</code> and companion classes <code>A$class</code> and <code>B$class</code>. class <code>C</code> simply forwards the methods to the static companion classes. Self-types are not enforced at all, lambdas are transpiled on compile-time to abstract inner classes, so is a <code>new D with A with B</code> expression. Pattern-matching is a bunch of if-else structures. Non-local returns? try-catch mechanism from the lambda. Anything left? (Interestingly, my scalac says 1.6 is the default)"
    }, {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 6803779,
        "reputation" : 742,
        "user_id" : 5236247,
        "user_type" : "registered",
